### For Loop in Go

Go has only one looping construct: `for`. It is extremely flexible.

### Classic For Loop

```go
for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
    fmt.Println(i)
}
```

Components: initialization, condition, post-increment. All are optional.

### Infinite Loop

```go
for {
    fmt.Println("runs forever")
    break // exit loop
}
```

### For with Only Condition

```go
sum := 1
for sum < 100 {
    sum += sum
}
fmt.Println(sum) // 128
```

### Initialization Scope

Variables declared in the init statement are scoped to the loop:

```go
for i := 0; i < 10; i++ {
    // i is accessible here
}
// i is NOT accessible here
```

### Loop Labels

Labels allow breaking or continuing outer loops:

```go
outer:
for i := 0; i < 3; i++ {
    for j := 0; j < 3; j++ {
        if i+j > 3 {
            break outer
        }
        fmt.Printf("(%d,%d) ", i, j)
    }
}
```

### Loop Variable Capture (Go 1.22+)

Since Go 1.22, loop variables have per-iteration scope:

```go
for i := 0; i < 3; i++ {
    go func() {
        fmt.Println(i) // 0, 1, 2 (correct in Go 1.22+)
    }()
}
```

> **Key Point:** Go's `for` is the only loop keyword. It covers all looping patterns (C-style for, while, infinite loops).

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    fmt.Println("Classic for:")
    for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
        fmt.Printf("%d ", i)
    }
    fmt.Println()

    fmt.Println("Condition-only for:")
    sum := 1
    for sum < 100 {
        sum *= 2
    }
    fmt.Println("Sum:", sum)
}
